erent kinds of trees such as denser areas of the forest axlewood, and flame forest trees. Near the lake and watering holes, you\'ll find mangoes, Arjun, and black plum trees. Tadoba is also home to many wild deciduous trees like Semal, Crepe myrtle (Mahua Machuca), crocodile bark (Ain), Dhauda, Hirda, Hald, Tendu, Salai, Bor Bel, Surya, Karaya Gum, Kusum Mahua, Shisham, Lanneacormandelica, Chichwa, Mowai, Rohan, Dhawada, Phetra, Sisoo, Sirus, Shivan, Jamun, Bel, Char, Ber, Harra, and tamarind.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"22px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:22px\">Other trees in Tadoba National Park are useful for humans such as:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1. Ain Tree: </strong>Its bark is fire-resistant and used in making musical instruments, furniture, boats, and railroad ties.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. Semal Tree: </strong>Also known as the Malabar silk cotton tree, it yields cotton used in the Malabar region.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3. Shisham Tree:</strong> Also known as North Indian rosewood, it\'s popular for furniture-making, and its fruits can be used for organic pesticides.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Kusum Tree:</strong> Its seeds are used for oil, which is used in various industries, including personal care.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These trees not only add to the beauty of the park but also have practical uses for local communities and industries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"22px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:22px\"><strong>Medicinal Plants of Tadoba National Park</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The grassland regions of Tadoba contain various species of grasses and medicinal plants, including velvet bean creepers (KachKujali), Bija, Ceylon satinwood, Bheria, Neem, Beheda, Orthosiphon Rubicundus and Heria. The park\'s rich biodiversity includes many more plants with medicinal value, which have been used by local communities for generations to treat various ailments.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"22px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:22px\"><strong>Shrubs of Tadoba National Park&nbsp;</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Tadoba National Park, the dry deciduous forest area is home to 28 varieties of <strong>shrubs, including 17 climber species.</strong> These shrubs play an important role in the ecosystem. Some of the commonly found shrubs in the region include Grewia Rothii, Aristolochia Indica, Cryptolepis Buchanani, Helicteres Isora, and&nbsp; Grewia Hirsuta. Since different parts of the forest receive varying amounts of sunlight and moisture, the types and density of shrub species may vary in different areas of the park. These shrubs provide habitat and food for various animals and birds, contributing to the biodiversity of Tadoba National Park.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"fontSize\":\"22px\"}}} -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" style=\"font-size:22px\"><strong>&nbsp;Herbs of Tadoba National Park</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Tadoba National Park, there are a total of <strong>159 species of herbaceous plants</strong> observed in different parts. The largest number of herb species are found during the monsoon season because the temperature and rainfall are just right for their growth. Some of the most common herb species found in Tadoba include Urginea Indica, Grange Maderaspatana, Lathyrus Sativus, Chlorophytum Tuberosum, Orthosiphon Rubicundus, Chlorophytum Laxum, Murdannia Edulis, Scilla Hyacynthiana, Melilotus 