d you, if you find langurs or sambar deer quickly starts moving, or you find unusual distinct calls made by birds in silence then know that the tiger is going to make his move. Another way of finding the tiger is by spotting his pug marks on the soil by the road and near water bodies. Try to follow those marks to spot him, but do follow the rules and regulations of the forest, and don’t ask the driver to go into prohibited areas.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4. Choose the right safari</strong> - Tadoba National Park offers two types of vehicles for a safari - a jeep and a canter. It is advised to always pick a jeep because it offers a quiet ride and it can go deep inside the forest. Jeep safaris cost more than canter but they have advantages that offer better sighting opportunities. Canters are bigger in size so they tend to be on the main roads. Which in turn reduces the chances of spotting a tiger,&nbsp; especially if the forest is dense and has no water bodies by the road.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5. Book Multiple Safaris</strong> - If you’re going to Tadoba, especially for spotting tigers then make sure to book multiple safaris because the wildlife sightings are unpredictable and it totally depends on luck. If you book more safaris then you can spend more time inside the jungle and spending more time inside means that you have more chances to spot wild animals inside the park.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>6. Stay at a nearby accommodation</strong> - If you’re coming to Tadoba and you’re going on safaris 2 times a day then staying at the nearby accommodation would be beneficial. Doing 2 safaris in a day will take around 8 hours to complete and if you choose to stay at a far place then it will take a lot of time to commute to and from your resort. Being late may cost you a sight and also it will tire you a lot so you won’t b